<HEADLINE>
<P>
MORNING REPORT: VIDEO RENTALS; 
</P>
<P>
CAN 'BAD INFLUENCE' OVERTAKE 'DAISY'? 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DENNIS HUNT , Arts and entertainment reports from The Times, national and 
international news services and the nation's press. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Who's going to drive "Driving Miss Daisy" out of the top spot of the Billboard 
magazine rental chart? Maybe it will be "Bad Influence," the sordid thriller 
starring Rob Lowe and James Spader, which is the hottest new video to hit the 
market since "Miss Daisy" cruised in back in early August. "Miss Daisy" has 
been so strong that it's kept "Born on the Fourth of July" -- which has been 
doing big rental business -- in second place. 
</P>
<P>
Zany "Nuns on the Run" sprinted from No. 21 to No. 14 and is a good bet to 
crack the Top 10. So far, renters haven't been that mad about "Madhouse," the 
madcap Kristie Alley comedy, which moved up just one notch to No. 17 in its 
second chart week. Debuts: the hip-hop movie "House Party" (No. 23) and 
"Nightbreed," which could be a big Halloween title. 
</P>
<P>
* This remake of a famed 1937 tear-jerker wasn't quite as big as expected in 
theaters, though the gross -- $20 million -- was respectable. But it could be a 
big home video hit, thanks to the drawing power of stars Bette Midler and John 
Goodman. In its second chart week, "Stella" jumped from No. 12 to No. 8. 
</P>
<P>
VIDEO RENTALS 
