<HEADLINE>
<P>
ROLL CALL: THE HOUSE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Paying for Troops in Japan 
</P>
<P>
The House voted 370 to 53 to require Japan to pay the $5-billion annual cost of 
stationing 50,000 U. S. troops and dependents there. This occurred during 
debate on the fiscal 1991 defense budget (HR 4739). About 5,000 of the 
Americans would be withdrawn annually if Japan declined to start paying for 
them. U. S. troops are based in Japan to protect it as well as American 
regional interests. 
</P>
<P>
Sponsor David E. Bonior (D-Mich.) complained that "American workers are paying 
to protect Japan while Japan closes its markets to us." 
</P>
<P>
Opponent David O'B. Martin (R-N.Y.) said the amendment sends Japan an 
appropriate message but "would be more detrimental to the United States." 
</P>
<P>
A yes vote was to require Japan to begin paying for the American troops it 
hosts. 
</P>
