<P>
</P>
<P>
Troops in Korea 
</P>
<P>
By a vote of 157 to 265, the House rejected an amendment to bring more troops 
home from South Korea than the White House wants returned as world tensions 
ease. The amendment to the 1991 defense bill (above) sought to reduce U. S. 
forces in South Korea from 43,000 to 30,000 in the next few years, contrasted 
with the 36,000 level sought by the Pentagon. 
</P>
<P>
Sponsor Robert J. Mrazek (D-N.Y.) said his amendment "would save us $3 billion 
over the next five years without affecting our deterrence capability." 
</P>
<P>
Opponent Robert J. Lagomarsino (R-Ventura) said: "North Korea has done nothing 
really to . . . change its dictatorial policies to warrant us lowering our 
guard." 
</P>
<P>
A yes vote was to cap U. S. military strength in South Korea at 30,000. 
</P>
